snippet.textDisplay:
I don't understand. 
Novak was cleared with medical exemption that he has medical conditions and he unable to take vaccine. Secondly, he provided details that he has contracted COVID in mid December that is within 30 days of his arrivals. 
So yes, on these basis both Independent medical examiners of ATP and Victorian Government granted him the exemption. 
That's fine - all good.

Now, the problem is  Mr Djokovic :
1. Said in his visa application that he has not travel to any other country within 15 days or so prior to arriving Australia. But he did travel to Spain as per reports and as per his social media accounts.
2. Said he contracted COVID around 16th - But he was seen in public interaction on 17th. But then he said he got his report on 17th itself. But he was again seen giving interviews to journalist on 18th as well. So he is for sure not following the basic protocols of  self isolation for 7/10 days.

So how can a Government of another country knowingly allow such person - who is evading protocols, who is committing fraud by denying that he didn't travel anywhere and who, along with his family, is unable to justify his public appearances even after testing positive of COVID ?
In my opinion the Australian Govt. the judiciary took the right steps to deport Mr Djokovic. Because, then the Government cannot justify such preferential treatment for celebrities while the common Australians are subjected to harsh lockdowns and mandatory vaccine regulations.
